Combat Modification System
==========================
The combat modification system is a system for applying temporary mods
to combat. The system is included by all LIVINGs and provides hooks to
interact with combat modifying objects. The system requires that an
object with functions to set modifications be registered with the
living whose combat is to be modified.


Registering combat mod objects
------------------------------
  void add_combat_adj(object oArg)
    - This function must be called on the living that will get the mods.
      The object passed is registered with the living as an object which
      modifies combat for that living.

  void remove_combat_adj(object oArg)
    - This function should be called on the living when a particular
      modification to combat is unregistered.

  void add_tmp_to_XXX(int iAdjustment)
    - XXX to be replaced by a mod type.
      This function will add a temporary mod of the passed value.

  void query_tmp_to_XXX()
    - This function will return a temporary mod of the given type.

  void reset_tmp_to_XXX()
   - This function will reset the mod of the given type to 0.

The following modifications exist:
  tmp_to_hit_stat
  tmp_to_dam_stat
  tmp_to_dodge_stat
  tmp_to_absorb_stat
  tmp_to_crit_stat
  tmp_to_hit
  tmp_to_crit
  tmp_to_dam
  tmp_to_dodge
  tmp_to_absorb
  tmp_to_type
  tmp_to_swings

The crit modifications are critical damage modifiers. They do not alter
the chance that an attack becomes a critical hit.
Use STATUS_EXPOSED from <status_effects.h> for incoming critical chance.
See `wizhelp 9.16` for the living-owned status-effect API.

Functions to define in combat mod object
----------------------------------------
  int modify_combat(object oTarget)
    - This is called by the attacking living, at the start of the combat
      round. The target is the current target being attacked. The return
      value is currently unused, and not tmp mods are expected to be set.

  int modify_attack(object oTarget, mixed* axAtt)
    - This is called by the attacking living, prior to an attack set axAtt
      being launched at oTarget. The return value is currently unused, and
      the following tmp mods are cleared prior to this function being
      called: tmp_to_hit_stat, tmp_to_dam_stat, tmp_to_crit_stat,
      tmp_to_swings.

  int modify_swing(object oTarget, mixed* axAtt)
    - This is called by the attacking living, prior to each swing of an
      attack set axAtt being launched at oTarget. The return value is
      currently unused, and the following tmp mods are cleared prior to
      this function being called: tmp_to_hit, tmp_to_crit.
      
  int modify_hit(object oTarget, mixed* axAtt, status tCrit)
    - This is called by the attacking living, once it has been determined
      that contact will be made, but before damage is determined. The
      return value is currently unused, and the following tmp mods are
      cleared prior to this function being called: tmp_to_dam, tmp_to_type.

  int modify_get_attacked(object oAttacker, mixed* axAtt)
    - This is called by the defending living, prior to an attack set axAtt
      being launched by oAttacker. The return value is currently unused, and
      the following tmp mods are cleared prior to this function being
      called: tmp_to_dodge_stat, tmp_to_absorb_stat.

  int modify_swung_at(object oAttacker, mixed* axAtt)
    - This is called by the defending living, prior to each swing of an
      attack set axAtt being made by oAttacker. The return value is
      currently unused, and the following tmp mods are cleared prior to this
      function being called: tmp_to_dodge.
      
  int modify_get_hit(object oAttacker, int iDam, int iType, status tCrit)
    - This is called by the defending living, after contact has been made
      and damage determined, but prior to damage actually being applied.
      The return value is currently unused, and the following tmp mods are
      cleared prior to this function being called: tmp_to_absorb.

  int filter_standard_block(int iBlock, string sEffectId)
    - This is called by the blocked living when set_standard_block() is
      about to apply a standard block. The value of iBlock is the current
      block mask, possibly already modified by earlier combat mod objects.
      The value of sEffectId is the effect id passed to set_standard_block().

      Return the block mask that should continue being applied. Returning
      0, or any value less than 1, prevents the block from being applied.
      Returning iBlock leaves the block unchanged. A filter may also remove
      individual block bits from iBlock before returning it.

      The living-side dispatcher for this hook is
      apply_filter_standard_block(int iBlock, string sEffectId). It calls
      filter_standard_block() on each registered combat mod object in order
      before the living's normal noblocks mask is applied.


How much of a bonus to give?
----------------------------
The easiest way to give bonuses/penalties is with tmp_to_WHATEVER_stat.
This effectively lowers the living's stat in one of the four combat
areas as if they had a lower physical stat. The critical variants add
to damage before the critical multiplier is applied. Bear in mind that
actual combat stats are not as important as their relative ratios,
meaning that one point of temporary combat stat is far more valuable
to someone with one point of real stat than to someone that already
has fifty points. When giving out larger bonuses, it may be useful to
scale those bonuses in terms of a living's level or actual stat.

tmp_to_WHATEVER will increase the final values in a meaningful way.
For example, if one wants to guarantee a hit, an increase to tmp_to_hit
of 100 (or more) may be appropriate. In order to increase the actual
damage done by a hit, increase the tmp_to_dam by the amount desired.
Note that this method is usually much harder to balance.
